 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Introduction to Geopandas"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Geopandas is a package that builds on Pandas syntax, but allows you to work with geospatial data.  It has a number of dependencies, including fiona and shapely, but if you're using the class environment, you should be in good shape already."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import geopandas"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# We'll import a few other tools we'll need now, too.\n",
    "\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn\n",
    "import statsmodels.api as sm\n",
    "import statsmodels.formula.api as smf"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Geopandas is probably most often used to load local data, like shapefiles.  For instance, if we download some <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.naturalearthdata.com/http//www.naturalearthdata.com/download/110m/cultural/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.zip\">Nautral Earth</A> data and unzip it, we can load it."
   ]

    "# Since the distribution is highly skewed, we might zoom in a bit, by only looking at countries with a GDP of less than 5 million.\n",
    "# We're using the \"loc\" function in pandas to subset / make a selection.  This is what we generally refer to as \"indexing\" and \n",
    "# it follows the same conventions as numpy.  You can read more about indexing on the Pandas documentation:\n",
    "# https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/indexing.html\n",
    "\n",
    "_ = plt.hist(df.loc[df['gdp_md_est'] < 5000000,'gdp_md_est'],bins=50)"
   ]

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},

    "## Layers"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Layers are easily generated as well.  In this case, the first layer is plotted, and then the object from that is stored.  That \"base\" object is then passed to the next layer's plot method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "world = geopandas.read_file(geopandas.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres'))\n",
    "cities = geopandas.read_file(geopandas.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_cities'))\n",
    "\n",
    "base = world.plot(color='white', edgecolor='black')\n",
    "cities.plot(ax=base, marker='o', color='red', markersize=5);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Projections"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Geopandas can project your data easily.  The most common way is to use EPSG codes, which can be looked up in many places.  I use <a href=\"http://spatialreference.org/\" target=\"_blank\">spatialreference.org</a>/"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x215026e70c8>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 24,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "world = geopandas.read_file(geopandas.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres'))\n",
    "# Remove Antarctica!\n",
    "world = world[(world.name != \"Antarctica\") & (world.name != \"Fr. S. Antarctic Lands\")]\n",
    "# Reproject and plot\n",
    "world = world.to_crs(epsg=3395)\n",
    "world.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## More complicated projections"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# If your projection doesn't have an EPSG code, you can pass a Proj4 string to define a projection.\n",
    "# Graticule and bounding box from natural earth: https://www.naturalearthdata.com/downloads/110m-physical-vectors/\n",
    "# For all the defined colors, see https://python-graph-gallery.com/100-calling-a-color-with-seaborn/\n",
    "\n",
    "proj4 = \"+proj=natearth\"\n",
    "\n",
    "bounding_box = geopandas.read_file(\"zip://data/ne_110m_wgs84_bounding_box.zip\")\n",
    "bounding_box = bounding_box.to_crs(proj4)\n",
    "\n",
    "world = geopandas.read_file(geopandas.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres'))\n",
    "world = world[(world.name != \"Antarctica\") & (world.name != \"Fr. S. Antarctic Lands\")]\n",
    "world = world.to_crs(proj4)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax = bounding_box.plot(color='lightgray')\n",
    "world.plot(ax=ax)\n",
    "_ = plt.axis('off')\n",
    "plt.savefig('out/natural_earth.png',dpi=300,bbox_inches='tight',pad_inches = 0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Geopandas is more than mapping"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Geopandas doesn't have all the features of a GIS, but many are available.  Take a look at the documentation here:\n",
    "<a href=\"http://geopandas.org/geometric_manipulations.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geopandas.org/geometric_manipulations.html</a> to see the full list.  Calculating buffers, centroids, convex hulls, and simplifying geometry are all readily accessible."
   ]
  },

    "# Dissolving"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<div>\n",
       "<style scoped>\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n",
       "        vertical-align: middle;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n",
       "        vertical-align: top;\n",

       "      <th></th>\n",
       "      <th>geometry</th>\n",
       "      <th>gop_2016_votes</th>\n",
       "      <th>totalvotes_2016</th>\n",
       "      <th>gop_prc_2016</th>\n",
       "    </tr>\n",

       "      <th></th>\n",

    "# We can group data with geopandas just as you'd expect, but we can also dissolve geometries with it:\n",
    "\n",
    "sub_df = df[['gop_2016_votes','totalvotes_2016','division','geometry']]\n",
    "groups = sub_df.dissolve(by='division',aggfunc='sum')\n",
    "groups['gop_prc_2016'] = 100 * groups.gop_2016_votes / groups.totalvotes_2016\n",
    "groups.head(2)"

    "# We might have an excel or CSV document with lat/lon in them.  How do we turn this into a GEOdataframe, not just a dataframe?\n",
    "\n",
    "n = 50\n",
    "lat = np.random.randint(low=-90,high=90,size=(n))\n",
    "lon = np.random.randint(low=-180,high=180,size=(n))\n",
    "df = pd.DataFrame({'lat':lat,'lon':lon})\n",
    "df.head(3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,

   "outputs": [],
